[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026833&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026833&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Our system has been doing what Steve Miller's does for about 1.5 years, with
one change: the @domain in our From: mail addresses (``andrew.cmu.edu'') is the
primary name (not a CNAME) of a real, live Internet host.  RFC822 tells us that
such domain names must not be abbreviations, and I read that as telling us that
they shouldn't be CNAMEs, either.  We have MX records set up for the
andrew.cmu.edu domain that ship incoming mail to three postoffice machines:
po3.andrew.cmu.edu, po2.andrew.cmu.edu, and (lastly) andrew.cmu.edu itself.
Clearly, mailers using MX records get their mail to andrew.cmu.edu via one of
these machines; mailers not using MX records get stuck with the overloaded
andrew.cmu.edu machine.

I have been gratified to see po3.andrew.cmu.edu gradually getting more loaded
with incoming mail as more sites move to mailers that deal with MX records.

I expect that Steve Miller's proposal will work just fine, too, but wouldn't it
be easier just to name one of the local hosts CS.UMD.EDU and thus remove any
possible objection?

                Craig

